<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">State and federal authorities have begun settlement talks with Commerzbank, Germanyâs second-largest lender, over the bankâs dealings with Iran and other countries blacklisted by the United States, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/07/u-s-scrutiny-for-banks-shifts-to-commerzbank-and-germany">Jessica Silver-Greenberg and Ben Protess write in DealBook</a></b>. The bank, which is suspected of transferring money through its American operations on behalf of companies in Iran and Sudan, could reach a settlement as soon as this summer. A potential deal is also expected to pave the way for a separate settlement with Deutsche Bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The settlement is expected to include <b>at least $500 million in penalties</b> for Commerzbank. Although prosecutors were still weighing punishments, people briefed on the matter said the bank would most likely face a so-called <b>deferred prosecution agreement</b>, which would suspend criminal charges in exchange for the financial penalty and other concessions. Last week, BNP Paribas, Franceâs largest bank, agreed to pay an $8.9 billion penalty and plead guilty to criminal charges for sanctions violations. The French banks CrÃ©dit Agricole and SociÃ©tÃ© GÃ©nÃ©rale also face investigations into whether they violated United States sanctions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCollectively, the deals will provide a <b>capstone to the decade-long investigation</b> into banks that opened the American financial system to tainted money,â Ms. Silver-Greenberg and Mr. Protess write. âThe investigations into the European banks, which funneled billions of dollars through their New York offices on behalf of foreign clients, underscored the reach of the United States sanctions laws as well as the <b>global demand to do business in dollars</b>.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares in Commerzbank <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/08/commerzbank-shares-fall-on-news-of-settlement-talks">fell about 3.5 percent</a></b> in Frankfurt on Tuesday after news of the settlement talks.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">SHORT-TERM RELIEF FOR PUERTO RICO UTILITY <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Puerto Ricoâs struggling electric power authority reached a temporary deal on Monday with some of its lenders to delay certain payments for three more weeks, buying the agency a little time as it sorts out its troubled finances, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/07/lenders-agree-to-give-puerto-rico-utility-more-time-to-repay-debt">Michael Corkery writes in DealBook</a></b>. The agreement forestalls a possible restructuring by the power authority, which supplies electricity to the islandâs 3.6 million residents. The Puerto Rico Electric Power Authority, known by its acronym Prepa, uses the credit lines provided by these lenders to purchase oil to generate electricity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Corkery writes</b>: âThe deal reflects the conundrum facing the power authorityâs lenders. Prepa owes money on two main credit lines â a roughly $250 million line from Citigroup and a $550 million line from a syndicate of banks. If Citigroup and the other lenders force Prepa to pay immediately, it could <b>hasten the authorityâs path to restructuring</b> and increase the likelihood of losses for the banks. Still, Prepaâs cash crisis cannot be fixed easily â which means a reckoning for its lenders may be inevitable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last week, Moodyâs Investors Service <b>downgraded Prepaâs credit rating</b> further into junk territory. According to Moodyâs, Prepa owes $146 million to Citigroup over the next two months. Itâs not clear when the authority must repay the bank syndicate the outstanding balance on its $550 million credit line.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ALLERGAN UNDER MOUNTING PRESSURE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Pershing Square Capital Management, the hedge fund run by William A. Ackman, proposed a slate of directors on Monday that it hoped to elect to the Allergan board, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/07/pershing-square-offers-slate-of-directors-for-allergan">David Gelles writes in DealBook</a></b>. Pershing Square, which is working with Valeant Pharmaceuticals on a $53 billion hostile bid for Allergan, is still trying to secure enough shareholder support to call a special meeting. Should the meeting be called, Pershing Square, which owns about 10 percent of Allergan, will try to <b>dismiss without cause six existing board members</b> and elect six new ones.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a statement on Monday afternoon, Allergan defended its board and <b>questioned Valeantâs motives</b>. âWe believe todayâs announcement is a further attempt by co-bidders Pershing Square and Valeant to acquire Allergan at a grossly inadequate price that substantially undervalues the company and creates significant risks and uncertainties for Allergan stockholders,â the company said.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The N.F.I.B. <b>small business optimism index</b> is out at 7:30 a.m. The <b>Job Openings and Labor Turnover Survey</b> is released at 10 a.m. Data on <b>consumer credit</b> is out at 3 p.m. <b>Jeffrey M. Lacker</b>, president of the Richmond Fed, gives a speech on the economic outlook at 1 p.m. in Charlotte, N.C. <b>Narayana Kocherlakota</b>, president of the Minneapolis Fed, gives a speech on monetary policy and the economy at 1:45 p.m. in Minnesota.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The <b>Senate Banking Committee</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. to examine the role of regulation in shaping equity market structure and electronic trading.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">SOLVING PRIVATE EQUITYâS RECRUITING PROBLEM <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Neither big investment banks nor private equity firms like the current recruiting process for young talent, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/07/one-way-to-solve-private-equitys-recruiting-problem">DealBookâs William Alden writes</a></b>. To fill their junior ranks, private equity firms <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/06/business/wall-street-banks-and-private-equity-firms-compete-for-young-talent.html">extend offers to low-level bankers</a></b> who are only six months into their careers, forcing the firms to evaluate workers who have little experience on Wall Street. For their part, bank executives contend that the recruiting process can create conflicts of interest for junior bankers because private equity firms are the banksâ clients.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To solve the problem, some private equity firms <b>recruit directly on college campuses</b>. Bain Capital, the Boston-based private equity firm, has for years hired young workers directly out of college. Kohlberg Kravis Roberts hired fresh college graduates this year for the first time. And the Carlyle Group hired one recent graduate for its Equity Opportunity Fund â the first time that particular fund had done so.</p>
</div>
